questions.explanation:
`WebSocket.bufferedAmount` is the count of bytes passed to `send()` that are still queued, not yet transmitted. If you call `send()` faster than the socket drains, it climbs — your cue to slow down (this is the WebSocket equivalent of stream backpressure).

```js
const HWM = 1_000_000; // 1 MB queued = too far behind
function maybeSend(ws, data) {
  if (ws.bufferedAmount < HWM) ws.send(data); // room to send
  // else: skip, coalesce, or disconnect this laggard
}
```

Both the browser API and Node's `ws` library expose `bufferedAmount`, so the same guard works on client and server.
